Connecting to a postgresql database

Start the rsm-msba or rsm-msba-spark computing container to also start postgresql. You can connect to the database using the code chunk below.

library(DBI)
library(RPostgres)
con <- dbConnect(
  dbDriver("Postgres"),
  user = "jovyan", 
  host = "127.0.0.1", 
  port = 8765,
  dbname = "rsm-docker",
  password = "postgres"
  ## use the line below in interactive settings
  # password = rstudioapi::askForPassword("Database password")
)

Is there anything in the data base? If this is not the first time you are running this Rmd file the data base should be available already (i.e., the code chunk below should show “flights” as an existing table)

library(dplyr)
library(dbplyr)
db_tabs <- dbListTables(con)
db_tabs
[1] "mtcars"  "flights"
mtcars

flights

If the database is empty, lets start with the example at https://db.rstudio.com/dplyr/ and work through the following 5 steps:

1. install the nycflights13 package

if (!require("nycflights13")) {
  install.packages("nycflights13")
}

2. Push data into the database

## only push to db if table does not yet exist
if (!"flights" %in% db_tabs) {
  copy_to(con, nycflights13::flights, "flights",
    temporary = FALSE,
    indexes = list(
      c("year", "month", "day"),
      "carrier",
      "tailnum",
      "dest"
    )
  )
}

3. Create a reference to the data base that (db)plyr can work with

flights_db <- tbl(con, "flights")

4. Query the data base using (db)plyr

flights_db %>% select(year:day, dep_delay, arr_delay)
flights_db %>% filter(dep_delay > 240)
flights_db %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(delay = mean(dep_time))
tailnum_delay_db <- flights_db %>% 
  group_by(tailnum) %>%
  summarise(
    delay = mean(arr_delay),
    n = n()
  ) %>% 
  window_order(desc(delay)) %>%
  filter(n > 100)

tailnum_delay_db
tailnum_delay_db %>% show_query()
<SQL>
SELECT *
FROM (SELECT "tailnum", AVG("arr_delay") AS "delay", COUNT(*) AS "n"
FROM "flights"
GROUP BY "tailnum") "q01"
WHERE ("n" > 100.0)
nrow(tailnum_delay_db)
[1] NA
tail(tailnum_delay_db)
Error: tail() is not supported by sql sources
tailnum_delay <- tailnum_delay_db %>% 
  collect() %>%
  mutate(n = as.integer(n))
nrow(tailnum_delay)
[1] 1201
tail(tailnum_delay)

Nothing will be stored in radiant unless you use the register function:

register("tailnum_delay")

You can now access the tailnum_delay data anywhere in the radiant application. For example, to make some histograms in Data > Visualize

visualize(
  tailnum_delay, 
  xvar = c("delay", "n"), 
  type = "dist", 
  custom = FALSE
)

5. Query the data using SQL

You can specify a SQL code chunk to query the database directly

SELECT * FROM flights WHERE dep_time > 2350
